<div id="review_1748364510" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1748364510" />
    <a title="David Huff" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22679327-david-huff"><img alt="David Huff" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567382988p2/22679327.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1748364510?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Huff" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Huff" href="/user/show/22679327-david-huff">David Huff</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385092883" href="/book/show/1990663.The_Waning_of_the_Middle_Ages">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1748364510" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11374701646865973269">Spending time browsing through &quot;Great Books&quot; lists tends to turn up classics like this one, and since my knowledge of the Middle Ages was scant at best, I thought I&apos;d give this older classic (published in 1924) a try. I was pleasantly surprised at Huizinga&apos;s writing style, which for the most part was quite interesting and engaging. His history largely covered France and the Netherlands, and dealt with a variety of characteristics of the 14th and 15th centuries; topics such as chivalry, vows, lov</span>
  <span id="freeText11374701646865973269" style="display:none">Spending time browsing through "Great Books" lists tends to turn up classics like this one, and since my knowledge of the Middle Ages was scant at best, I thought I'd give this older classic (published in 1924) a try. I was pleasantly surprised at Huizinga's writing style, which for the most part was quite interesting and engaging. His history largely covered France and the Netherlands, and dealt with a variety of characteristics of the 14th and 15th centuries; topics such as chivalry, vows, love and romance, death, religious views, the power of symbols, the art and literature of the period, and much more. <br /><br />There were quite a few quotes, some extensive, in French (fortunately with English footnotes), often from authors either obscure or unknown (at least to me). A familiarity with the Middle Ages may have helped me to grasp the plentiful content of this book more firmly, but I felt it was still a very good introduction to the period. Facts and anecdotes were nicely balanced with deeper philosophical passages. My only complaint, which had nothing to do with Huizinga, was the horribly inconsistently edited and sketchy Kindle edition. I would definitely recommend this book to anyone interested in the historical period - but in hardback or paperback.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11374701646865973269" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

