  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3902876723" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3902876723" />
    <a title="Wiom biom" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/55748187-wiom-biom"><img alt="Wiom biom" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608386569p2/55748187.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3902876723?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Wiom biom" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Wiom biom" href="/user/show/55748187-wiom-biom">Wiom biom</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3902876723" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16662565407156480661">I absolutely loved reading this book, which is the best-known work by Johan Huizinga, Dutch historian and one of the founders of modern cultural history! Without actively trying to, I found myself reading the text sentence by sentence which actually surprised myself as I tend to read quickly and resort to skimming even. The amount of concentration I devoted to reading this particular book was probably due to my pre-existing interest in the Middle Ages though it must be said that it was sustained</span>
  <span id="freeText16662565407156480661" style="display:none">I absolutely loved reading this book, which is the best-known work by Johan Huizinga, Dutch historian and one of the founders of modern cultural history! Without actively trying to, I found myself reading the text sentence by sentence which actually surprised myself as I tend to read quickly and resort to skimming even. The amount of concentration I devoted to reading this particular book was probably due to my pre-existing interest in the Middle Ages though it must be said that it was sustained largely due to the writing of Huizinga.<br /><br />Huizinga writes clearly and succinctly and what I appreciate the most about The Waning of the Middle Ages is the coherent flow of and the brevity of the chapters, which begin with describing broadly the patterns of thought that characterised the medieval mind and then exploring various ideas like chivalry, love, and religion, and finally comparing the verbal and plastic art forms of that period. <br /><br />Throughout the book, the thesis remains consistent: that the medieval mind was characterised by extremes, vacillating between pious tenderness and brutal cruelty, and that it was singularly 'immature' in that it sought to reduce any abstract idea to something tangible, most commonly seen in their attitude towards religion, which ranged from the deliberately impious to the casually superstitious. Additionally, Huizinga argues that the late Middle Ages is an example of cultural decline and exhaustion instead of rebirth and optimism which we associate with the renaissance. <br /><br />While I admire Huizinga's personal insights into the obscure and mysterious Middle Ages, there is something fundamentally troubling about the substantiation of his arguments. <br /><br />Indeed, according to Wikipedia, "Huizinga's work later came under criticism, especially for relying too heavily on evidence from the rather exceptional case of the Burgundian court." The sources that Huizinga rely on are of a highly limited nature and are unconvincing in shedding light on the lives of the masses as much as it does the manners and sentiments of the Burgundian nobility. Huizinga thus limits the scope of his argumentation to a small proportion of the population living in a small region in Europe. Furthermore, his arguments do not really resonate with me at times; for instance, the evidence he brings up to support his claim that the late Middle Ages was a time of cultural decline and exhaustion is the increasing use of ornamentation in art, whether it is in poetry or painting. I see how this makes sense when we consider also Mannerism during the Baroque phase of European art but still it is not very convincing in my opinion. Diving deeper into the text, one also gets the impression that there is nothing positive about the Middle Ages nor the late Middle Ages -- its people are simplistic, its poetry is stale, its art is mediocre. While he does claim that the late Middle Ages contained the seeds of the renaissance, whether in new forms that expressed old ideas or vice versa, it makes me wonder if Huizinga's writing was a product of its time when Enlightenment ideals were still very much celebrated as opposed to the 'self-imposed nonage' of the Middle Ages, as Kant so pithily described in his essay, "What is Enlightenment?" <br /><br />Still love me some cultural history though!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16662565407156480661" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

